				\begin{document}$${\varvec{O}}(\mathrm{T}\times \mathrm{N}\times \mathrm{D})$$\end{document}; third, the computational complexity of vertical crossover is12O(T×N×D)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{1}{2}{\varvec{O}}(\mathrm{T}\times \mathrm{N}\times \mathrm{D})$$\end{document}; Fourth, the computational complexity of horizontal crossover is12O(T×N×D)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{1}{2}{\varvec{O}}(\mathrm{T}\times \mathrm{N}\times \mathrm{D})$$\end{document}; finally, the competitive operator conducted after each crossover mechanism is2O(T×N)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$2{\varvec{O}}(\mathrm{T}\times \mathrm{N})$$\end{document}. Therefore, the total computational complexity of CCHHO is2O(N×(T×D+T+1))\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$2{\varvec{O}}(\mathrm{N}\times (\mathrm{T}\times \mathrm{D }+\mathrm{ T }+ 1) )$$\end{document}, in which T\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathrm{T}$$\end{document} is the maximum number of iterations and D\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathrm{D}$$\end{document} is the dimension of the problem. It can be seen that the introduction of crisscross strategy into HHO makes the computational time increase one time, but does not rise the computational complexity.

In each experimental case, every chosen approach runs 30 times independently aiming at weakening the impact of randomness on experimental results. Also, the population size is set to 30. In computational intelligence, a matter of fact is the fairness of computational testing [71]. According this rule, we can make sure the obtained results are justifiably recorded without bias toward one or other algorithm [72]. The setup of initial parameters of all algorithms was identical with their original references. The setup of the parameters in all the comparing algorithms are recorded in Table1.Table 1
